* {{ill|Ōgetsuhime|ja|オオゲツヒメ}} (Ōgetsuhime no Mikoto) — also known as Amanoiwatowake Yakurahime no Mikoto (天石門別八倉比売命) or Ōawa-hime no Mikoto (大粟比売命).

According to shrine tradition, Ōgetsuhime traveled from the Niwa region of {{ill|Ise Province|ja|伊勢国}} (present-day {{ill|Taki, Mie|ja|多気町}}, {{ill|Mie Prefecture|ja|三重県}}) to Awa Province on horseback and introduced the cultivation of {{ill|millet|ja|粟}} to the area.

== History ==
This shrine is one of the disputed sites claiming to be the {{ill|Shikinai Taisha|ja|式内大社}} "Ama no Iwatowake Yakurahime Shrine" listed in the {{ill|Engishiki|ja|延喜式}}. The shrine was designated as an imperial prayer site by Emperor {{ill|Shōmu|ja|聖武天皇}} in {{ill|Jinki|ja|神亀}} 5 (728 CE) and granted the senior first rank (正一位) in {{ill|Genryaku|ja|元暦}} 2 (1185 CE). During the {{ill|Heian period|ja|平安時代}}, a branch shrine, {{ill|Ichinomiya Shrine (Tokushima)|ja|一宮神社 (徳島市)}}, was established in present-day {{ill|Tokushima City|ja|徳島市}}.

In {{ill|Meiji|ja|明治}} 3 (1870 CE), the shrine was renamed "Haniuneya Shrine" (埴生女屋神社), but due to petitions from the local parishioners, it was restored to its current name, Kamiichinomiya Ōawa Shrine, in Meiji 28 (1895 CE).

