'''Kamiichinomiya Ōawa Shrine''' (上一宮大粟神社) is a [[:en:Shinto shrine|Shinto shrine]] located in [[:en:Kamiyama, Tokushima|Kamiyama, Tokushima]], [[:en:Myōzai District, Tokushima|Myōzai District]], [[:en:Tokushima Prefecture|Tokushima Prefecture]]. It is one of the disputed shrines ({{ill|Ronsha|ja|論社|1=candidate shrines|2=ja|3=論社|lt=candidate|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ronsha|13=User:Immanuelle/candidate shrines|1=Engishiki_Jinmyōchō#Ronsha|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki_Jinmyocho|lt=Ronsha}}}}) claiming to be the [[:en:Ichinomiya|Ichinomiya]] of [[:en:Awa Province (Tokushima)|Awa Province]], identified with the "Ama no Iwatowake Yakurahime Shrine" (天石門別八倉比売神社) mentioned in the [[:en:Engishiki|Engishiki]].<ref>Other claimants include {{ill|Yakurahime Shrine|ja|八倉比売神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yakurahime Shrine|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 天石門別八倉比売神社|1=Yakurahime Shrine|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11390577}} and [[:en:Ichinomiya Shrine (Tokushima)|Ichinomiya Shrine (Tokushima)]].</ref> Its former shrine Rank was {{ill|Gōsha|ja|郷社|1=Gō-sha|qid=Q134917316}}{{efn|District Shrines|lt=Ken-sha|1=modern system of ranked Shinto shrines|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gōsha|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 近代社格制度|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q712534}}, and it is No. 73 on the {{ill|New Shikoku Mandala Pilgrimage|ja|新四国曼荼羅霊場|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/New Shikoku Mandala Pilgrimage|qq=|1=Shin-Shikoku Mandara Pilgrimage|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11501519}}.

== Enshrined deity ==
* {{ill|Ōgetsuhime|ja|オオゲツヒメ|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōgetsuhime|qq=|1=Ōgetsuhime|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q3261482}} (Ōgetsuhime no Mikoto) — also known as Amanoiwatowake Yakurahime no Mikoto (天石門別八倉比売命) or Ōawa-hime no Mikoto (大粟比売命).

According to shrine tradition, Ōgetsuhime traveled from the Niwa region of [[:en:Ise Province|Ise Province]] (present-day [[:en:Taki, Mie|Taki, Mie]], [[:en:Mie Prefecture|Mie Prefecture]]) to Awa Province on horseback and introduced the cultivation of {{ill|millet|ja|粟|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/millet|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to アワ|1=Setaria italica|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q161211}} to the area.

== History ==
This shrine is one of the disputed sites claiming to be the {{ill|Shikinai Taisha|ja|式内大社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shikinai Taisha|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 名神大社|1=Myōjin Taisha|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q9610964}} "Ama no Iwatowake Yakurahime Shrine" listed in the [[:en:Engishiki|Engishiki]]. The shrine was designated as an imperial prayer site by Emperor [[:en:Emperor Shōmu|Shōmu]] in [[:en:Jinki (era)|Jinki]] 5 (728 CE) and granted the senior first Rank (正一位) in [[:en:Genryaku|Genryaku]] 2 (1185 CE). During the [[:en:Heian period|Heian period]], a branch shrine, [[:en:Ichinomiya Shrine (Tokushima)|Ichinomiya Shrine (Tokushima)]], was established in present-day [[:en:Tokushima (city)|Tokushima City]].

In [[:en:Meiji era|Meiji era]] 3 (1870 CE), the shrine was renamed "Haniuneya Shrine" (埴生女屋神社), but due to petitions from the local parishioners, it was restored to its current name, Kamiichinomiya Ōawa Shrine, in Meiji 28 (1895 CE).

